    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE REDUCTION, SINGLE DRIVE AXLES: EATON - ASSEMBLE -
        PINION BEARING PRELOAD ADJUSTMENT (TRIAL BUILD-UP TEST)
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="hl1401204" svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="3">
        <title>PINION BEARING PRELOAD ADJUSTMENT (TRIAL BUILD-UP TEST)</title>
        <para>The pinion bearing spacer thickness controls bearing preload. The spacer size for correct preload can be
            predetermined by using a "Trial Build-Up" procedure as described below:
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Assemble pinion bearing cage, cups and bearing spacer (without pinion or oil seal) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401226">Figure 26</hotlnk>). Use nominal size spacer (
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl1401205">Chart 1
                    <xref refid="hl1401205"/>
                </hotlnk>
                ).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401226" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401226" filename="../figg14/G1401226.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Parts For Trial Build-Up</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>During assembly procedure, center bearing spacer between the two bearing cones.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lubricate bearings and place the assembly in the press. Position the spacer so that load is
                applied directly to the backface of the outer bearing cone (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401227">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401227" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401227" filename="../figg14/G1401227.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Measure Bearing Preload</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Apply press load to the assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl1401206">Chart 2
                    <xref refid="hl1401206"/>
                </hotlnk>
                ). Wrap soft wire or strong string around bearing cage, attach spring scale and pull steadily. Preload
                is correct when torque required to rotate pinion bearing cage is from 10 to 20 in-lbs. (1.1 to 2.3 N&#8226;m).
                This specification is translated into spring scale readings in
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl1401206">Chart 2
                    <xref refid="hl1401206"/>
                </hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If necessary, adjust pinion bearing preload by changing the pinion bearing spacer. A thicker
                spacer will decrease preload. A thinner spacer will increase preload.
            </para>
        </step1>
