        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Use a calibrated load cell to insure proper loading.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Use the correct size spacer. Do not use shim stock or grind spacers. These practices can lead to
                    loss of bearing preload and gear or bearing failure.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Once correct bearing preload has been established, note the spacer size used. Select a
                spacer 0.001 inch larger for use in the final pinion bearing cage assembly. The larger spacer
                compensates for slight "growth" in the bearings which occurs when they are pressed on the pinion shank.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>With the first stage of bearing preload adjustment ("Trial Build-Up") completed, continue
                        reassembly of bearing cage and pinion.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press inner bearing cone on pinion using a properly sized sleeve (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401228">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401228" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401228" filename="../figg14/G1401228.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Install Inner Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install bearing spacer (preselected during "Trial Build-Up Test") .</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install bearing cage and cup assembly on pinion. Insert outer bearing cone in cage, then
                press bearing cone and cage assembly on pinion.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Models 23105, 26105, 30105 only: Lubricate O-ring with a high viscosity oil or barium
                grease. Install O-ring on bearing cage.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">At this stage of pinion reassembly, recheck bearing preload adjustment by performing FINAL
                PINION BEARING PRELOAD TEST, following.
            </para>
        </step1>
